 should be investigated, not assumed, and that policies not matching people's lives are not likely to succeed.The empirical data, on which the argument is based, are first a unique body of data material collected 1982-1984 by the national women's organization, the OMM [when the author was employed as a sociologist in the organization] and secondly data resulting from more recent fieldwork in northern Mozambique. Importantly inspired by African post-colonial feminist lines of thinking, the book engages in a project of re-mapping and re-interpreting 'cultureand tradition'. In this context, the book investigates in particular matriliny [c. 40% of Mozambique's population live under conditions of matriliny] and female initiation. The findings open new avenues for gender politics, and for re-thinking sexuality and gender - in Africa and beyond. Signe Arnfred is Associate Professor, Dept of Society & Globalization, and Centre for Gender, Power & Diversity, Roskilde University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEqualityxSocial aspectszMozambique. 0aEquality; Social aspects; Mozambique. 0aGender identityxPolitical aspectszMozambique. 0aGender identityxSocial aspectszMozambique. 0aGender identity; Political aspects; Mozambique. 0aGender identity; Social aspects; Mozambique. 0aIdentity (Psychology)xSocial aspects. 0aIdentity (Psychology); Social aspects. 0aSex discriminationzMozambiquevCase studies. 0aSex discrimination; Mozambique; Case studies. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectszAfrica. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectszMozambiquevCase studies. 0aSex role; Political aspects; Africa. 0aSex role; Political aspects; Mozambique; Case studies. 0aWomenzMozambiquexSocial conditions. 0aWomen; Mozambique; Social conditions. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Stud